{"actual_usd":0.15606,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":190,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30642,"reply":"\"The short answer is yes — necessary, if God means to forgive without pretending evil is small.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees, white tie hanging straight, while morning light catches on the edge of the bench beside me.* \"The cross is where mercy and truth stop being rivals. If God just waved sin away, we'd call that mercy at the expense of justice; at the cross, He bears it Himself. That's why Christians don't talk about forgiveness as God deciding not to care, but as God caring so much He would carry the cost rather than leave us under it.\"\n\n*I rub a thumb along the worn edge of my Bible.* \"Now, I wouldn't claim to have that all packed into a tidy little box. But that's the center of it for me: the cross says my sin can be named honestly, and I am not thrown away. Was there a particular knot in that question you were tugging on?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.607945000000036,"run_id":"59a17a50-39f4-4ca5-a0c1-c14def02db48"}
